SIMPLE: rifle
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Rifle
<hw>Ri"fle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Rifled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Rifling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>rifler</ets> to rifle, sweep away; of uncertain origin. CF.
<er>Raff</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To seize and bear away by force;
to snatch away; to carry off.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Till time shall <qex>rifle</qex> every youthful grace.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To strip; to rob; to pillage.</def> <rj><au>Piers
Plowman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Stand, sir, and throw us that you have about ye:⟦br⟧
If not, we'll make you sit and <qex>rifle</qex> you.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To raffle.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>J.
Webster.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rifle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Rifle
<hw>Ri"fle</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To raffle.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chapman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To commit robbery.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rifle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Rifle
<hw>Ri"fle</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Akin to Dan. <ets>rifle</ets>, or
<ets>riffel</ets>, the rifle of a gun, a chamfer (cf. <ets>riffel</ets>,
<ets>riffel</ets>b⟦oum⟧sse, a rifle gun, <ets>rifle</ets> to rifle a
gun, G. <ets>riefeln</ets>, <ets>riefen</ets>, to chamfer, groove), and
E. <ets>rive</ets>. See <er>Rive</er>, and cf. <er>Riffle</er>,
<er>Rivel</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A gun, the inside of whose
barrel is grooved with spiral channels, thus giving the ball a rotary
motion and insuring greater accuracy of fire. As a military firearm it
has superseded the musket.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A body of
soldiers armed with rifles.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A strip of wood covered with emery or a similar
material, used for sharpening scythes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Rifle pit</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>a trench for
sheltering sharpshooters.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rifle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Rifle
<hw>Ri"fle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
grove; to channel; especially, to groove internally with spiral
channels; <as>as, to <ex>rifle</ex> a gun barrel or a
cannon</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To whet with a rifle. See <er>Rifle</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, 3.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Riflebird</ent>⟦br⟧
